1. Your user opens the app and opens the credential they need to refresh.

2. GOV.UK Wallet checks the credential and finds it has expired, been revoked by the issuer or passed its `expectedUpdate` date. The app shows the user a refresh button.

3. The user presses the credential refresh button in the app.

4. GOV.UK Wallet calls GOV.UK One Login to exchange the current refresh token for a new access token and refresh token.

5. GOV.UK One Login verifies the refresh token request.

6. GOV.UK One Login generates a new access token and refresh token.

7. GOV.UK One Login issues the new access token and refresh token to GOV.UK Wallet. 

8. GOV.UK Wallet generates a [proof of possession token](/issue-credentials/credential/#request-body) for the credential request.

9. GOV.UK Wallet sends a `POST` request to your `/credential` endpoint to request the credential. This request includes the access token issued by GOV.UK One Login (as a bearer token in the authorization header) and the proof of possession token generated by GOV.UK Wallet.

Once GOV.UK One Login issues the new access token and refresh token to GOV.UK Wallet, your service can [continue the credential issuance process](/issue-credentials/#your-service-issues-a-credential).